                  <Abstract ID="Abs1" Language="En">
                     <Heading>Abstract</Heading>
                     <Para>The Schwarzschild space is one of the best studied space-times, and its exhaustive considerations are easily accessible. Nevertheless, for some reasons it is still surrounded by a lot of misconceptions, myths, and “paradoxes”. In this pedagogical paper, an attempt is made to give a simple (i.e., without cumbersome calculations) but rigorous consideration of the relevant questions. I argue that (1) an observer falling into a Schwarzschild black hole will <Emphasis Type="Italic">not</Emphasis> see “the entire history of the Universe“, (2) he will <Emphasis Type="Italic">not</Emphasis> cross the horizon at the speed of light, (3) when inside the hole, he will <Emphasis Type="Italic">not</Emphasis> see the (future) singularity, and (4) the latter is <Emphasis Type="Italic">not</Emphasis> “central“.</Para>
                  </Abstract>
